{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9170fb93-30bc-4105-a99c-8451c23fb0a9","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the workloads you already have **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → workloads need newer versions → use `update`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf you still see issues after that, also try `dotnet workload restore` from your project directory — it ensures all workloads referenced in your project are installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90cebc52-d6cc-4793-9bfc-6dbfe15794e0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":251},"id":"523c9cd1-6321-4c88-91d6-94b7f6ba5d63","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:49:32.145Z","parentId":"ee71adc5-606a-4c01-bbf3-d2effb138060"}
